### Problem Area
- In the aggregate step (`is_agg`), the code does:
  - `zval_ptr_dtor(&agg_context->val);` (line 444)
  - `zval_ptr_dtor(Z_REFVAL(agg_context->val));` (line 447)
  - `ZVAL_COPY_VALUE(Z_REFVAL(agg_context->val), &retval);` (line 448)
- The finalization and error paths may also call `zval_ptr_dtor(&agg_context->val);` (line 437).

### Issue
- The same memory may be freed twice, or a reference may be decremented after it has already been destroyed, leading to a use-after-free.

### Solution
- After calling `zval_ptr_dtor`, set the zval to `UNDEF` to avoid double-destruction.
- Ensure that we do not call `zval_ptr_dtor` on an already undefined zval.
- In the aggregate step, after moving the value, ensure the source is set to `UNDEF`.

